<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12119j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12119j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12119j"> 119(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Mel Beniget / stone mallet to kill O.M. / impotent</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Enfin, au temps jadis, on avait comme recours supr&ecirc;me le <i><mark>Mel Beniget</mark></i> (La Boule b&eacute;nite). &laquo;On apelle ainsi, dit M. Aveneau de la Granci&egrave;re, des massues, soit en bois, v&eacute;ritable <mark>maillets</mark>, &eacute;videmment renouvel&eacute;es dans le cours des si&egrave;cles, soit <mark>en pierre</mark>. Ces massues, conserv&eacute;es encore dans quelques chapelles du Morbihan et du sud-ouest des C&ocirc;tes-du-Nord, servaient, para&icirc;t-il, on ne sait plus quand, bien entendu, <mark>&agrave;assommer les vieillards impotents et inutiles</mark>. <small> Fran&ccedil;ois Cadic, <a name="NCEL" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#NCEL"><cite title="source">Nouveaux contes et l&eacute;gendes de Bretagne</cite></a> (1922) 55</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In the old days in Breton, people lived to be so old that ultimately it was necessary to stove their heads in with a hallowed mallet, made of stone and carefully preserved in each neighbourhood, usually in old chapels. </mm> </dd></dl>
